  accentWord="Groundworkers"
  subhead="You are at the controls of a six-tonne excavator when a builder calls about foundations for a new build. They hang up after two rings. Five seconds later, they get a text: 'Sorry we missed your call — we are on site. Back to you within the hour.' They wait. The next groundworker never gets the call."
  scenario="It is 9:15am on a Tuesday. You are loading a dumper on a ten-plot development in Wigan — reversing up a ramp with a full bucket of spoil and both hands on the levers. A builder from a different firm calls about subcontract groundwork on a single-storey extension in Leigh — they need someone next Monday, just a day-and-a-half of foundation work with a quick drain connection. Your phone rings twice in the cab and goes to voicemail. The builder does not leave a message — he has five other groundworkers in his phone and starts calling down the list. Then his phone buzzes: 'Thanks for calling Greenfield Groundworks. Sorry we missed your call — we are operating plant on site. We will ring you back by 10:30. If it is urgent, reply to this text.' He puts his phone down and waits. At 10:15, you call him back from the site cabin. He describes the Leigh job. You confirm Monday availability. Job booked — from a call you never even answered."
